WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt;Heath Row: Thank you for coming to Authors
at Google today.

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:05.770
My name is Heath Row.

00:00:05.770 --> 00:00:08.520
And I'm here to introduce Bonnie Schneider.

00:00:08.520 --> 00:00:15.019
Bonnie is a meteorologist appearing on various
media platforms, including CNN and HLN.

00:00:15.019 --> 00:00:18.390
She's also an author of a new non-fiction
book, "Extreme Weather," which you should

00:00:18.390 --> 00:00:20.570
have copies of.

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:25.400
Bonnie is the on-camera extreme weather expert
and co-executive producer of a new special

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:31.619
on the DIY Network called "Last House Standing,"
premiering at the end of March.

00:00:31.619 --> 00:00:35.120
Produced by Tara Productions, it's a one-hour
special that shows homeowners everything they

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:40.620
need to know about being proactive to protect
their homes from hurricane-force winds, torrential

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:43.550
rains, and devastating earthquakes.

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:47.730
Being in Southern California, hopefully we'll
learn a little bit today about mudslides,

00:00:47.730 --> 00:00:50.530
wildfires, and the Santa Ana winds.

00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:52.660
Ladies and gentlemen, Bonnie Schneider.

00:00:52.660 --> 00:00:53.660
[applause]

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:57.079
&gt;&gt;Bonnie Schneider: Thank you all so much
for having me.

00:00:57.079 --> 00:01:00.640
It is such a pleasure to be here at Google
and to be in California.

00:01:00.640 --> 00:01:04.850
I was just here a month ago to shoot this
special, "Last House Standing," for DIY.

00:01:04.850 --> 00:01:10.760
We went to Northridge, the site of a major
earthquake in 1994, and recapped what happened

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:12.430
and retrofit some homes.

00:01:12.430 --> 00:01:14.479
So, I look forward to sharing that special
with you.

00:01:14.479 --> 00:01:17.450
I have a handout on it on the DIY Network
on March 30th.

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:23.020
Well, without further ado, I wanna get to
my book, "Extreme Weather," which really was

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:25.590
an amazing experience for me to write.

00:01:25.590 --> 00:01:27.670
And I'm so excited that the book is finally
out.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:31.579
It seemed like it took forever to get it all
together--to get it written and on the shelves.

00:01:31.579 --> 00:01:32.710
And now, it's here.

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:37.590
So, this book is a survival guide to all types
of extreme weather.

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:42.049
Here in California, a lot of people outside
of California, think you guys have perfect

00:01:42.049 --> 00:01:45.290
weather all the time, but you, as residents,
you know that's not the case.

00:01:45.290 --> 00:01:48.549
There's quite a bit of extreme weather in
the State of California.

00:01:48.549 --> 00:01:53.940
And through the research of this book, I actually
spoke to many experts in California as well

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:56.579
as storm survivors in California.

00:01:56.579 --> 00:02:01.880
You can see my book covers many topics, including
flash floods, tornadoes, hurricanes, wildfire,

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:06.450
heat waves, snowstorms, tsunamis, all types
of natural disasters.

00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:12.090
And specifically for two of the chapters,
I spoke to storm survivors here in California.

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:15.920
And the first one was the land slide chapter.

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:20.849
And some of you may remember the devastating
land slide that occurred in La Conchita, California,

00:02:20.849 --> 00:02:22.170
in 2005.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:23.170
People were killed.

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:24.170
It was a real tragedy.

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:28.189
It was in January, so right around this time
of year.

00:02:28.189 --> 00:02:33.319
One of the women I interviewed was a young
woman--18 years old--and she was staying in

00:02:33.319 --> 00:02:36.510
La Conchita because she was in school in Santa
Barbara.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:38.190
And she was heading to class.

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:40.260
The winter semester had just begun.

00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:43.200
They just finished the Christmas break.

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:46.780
And it had been raining for days, but she
still wanted to get a head start and head

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:47.780
out to school.

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:53.070
So, she got on the road heading from La Conchita
to Santa Barbara, only to find mud flow ahead

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:54.400
of her and behind her.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:56.900
Eventually, they shut down the highway.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:03:01.090
And while it was inconvenient, she figured
that was really the worst of it.

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:05.159
Officials came and told her she had to leave
her car on the road.

00:03:05.159 --> 00:03:06.849
And she did, along with many other residents.

00:03:06.849 --> 00:03:08.489
And they took them back to town.

00:03:08.489 --> 00:03:11.840
And she decided she'd just sit it out and
go back to her house.

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:16.770
So, she goes to the upper level of her house,
which was where the living room was.

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:20.909
And just when she picked up her cell phone
to make a call, she noticed that a side of

00:03:20.909 --> 00:03:23.659
the wall was buckling in.

00:03:23.659 --> 00:03:27.680
And something told her this wasn't an earthquake
because it wasn't a shaking motion.

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:29.459
It wasn't happening on both sides of the house.

00:03:29.459 --> 00:03:31.909
It was just one side of the house.

00:03:31.909 --> 00:03:37.630
So, instinctively, she grabbed her phone and
started to dart down the stairs to exit the

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:38.630
house.

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:43.580
And just then, she felt dirt coming on top
of her face and hitting her in the eye.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:44.610
And that's all she remembers.

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:47.430
The entire house collapsed around her.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:51.960
And just by sheer luck, she was on that staircase.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:56.770
So the staircase, the way she fell, acted
as a barrier.

00:03:56.770 --> 00:04:01.670
And along with a bookcase that collapsed just
at the top of her, but not on her, it gave

00:04:01.670 --> 00:04:07.610
her a triangle area where she could breathe
and survive this devastating landslide.

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:12.890
Unbeknownst to her, there was a neighbor of
hers who was heading in the other direction

00:04:12.890 --> 00:04:14.700
on the highway when the mud flow closed it.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:18.220
He was heading home from work, He was an ER
nurse, returning from Santa Barbara to La

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:19.560
Conchita.

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:20.840
And he had done an overnight shift.

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:24.750
And instead of going home to bed, he got on
his bicycle and decided he's gonna look around

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:26.120
the neighborhood and see what's going on.

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:27.660
Well, sure enough, he saw-.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.360
First, he heard that popping sound of the
landslide.

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:36.620
And then, he saw it, the whole hill side crushing
down on the town and on homes.

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:41.220
So he got on his bicycle and he started just,
he got off where he thought was the worst

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:42.220
of the area.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:44.030
And he just called out, "I'm here to help.

00:04:44.030 --> 00:04:45.580
Can I help you?"

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:49.560
And he heard muffled cries of not just Nicole,
the young woman who was trapped, but many

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:50.560
people.

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:55.930
So, he just listened to where he could hear
the loudest sound and just dug with his hands.

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:59.530
And he managed to find Nicole and rescue her.

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:02.960
And she had a bad gash on her leg, but she
survived.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:07.370
And miraculously, these two were reunited
again.

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:11.960
And Bill, the man who found Nicole, was invited
to her wedding about a year or two later.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:16.800
And her grandmother grabbed his hands and
just said, "You saved our daughter's life."

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:20.850
And I have stories like this throughout the
book at the beginning of every chapter of

00:05:20.850 --> 00:05:24.229
"Extreme Weather," people that I've interviewed
directly.

00:05:24.229 --> 00:05:26.050
Some of the stories you've never heard before.

00:05:26.050 --> 00:05:27.460
Some are exclusive to the book.

00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:32.480
But this book isn't just about survivor stories,
even though every chapter has one.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.800
It really gets into practical, how-to advice
because I think all of us can agree that extreme

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:42.139
weather can happen at any time to any one
in any circumstance.

00:05:42.139 --> 00:05:47.479
And this was just a young woman going to school
and she got caught up in almost a tragedy

00:05:47.479 --> 00:05:49.020
of loss of life.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:51.050
But she survived.

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:56.490
So many of the people that I interviewed were
on their way to work or to school or on a

00:05:56.490 --> 00:05:59.490
vacation when this extreme weather struck.

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:06.010
So, it was my goal with this book to provide
readers with the information they would need

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:08.930
to be proactive to prepare for extreme weather.

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:13.890
And that means not only preparing, but also
giving practical advice of what to do if you're

00:06:13.890 --> 00:06:18.961
in your car and the road floods, what to do
if you're on foot during a snow storm, or

00:06:18.961 --> 00:06:22.949
how to react in you're in an office building
and there's an earthquake, which can happen

00:06:22.949 --> 00:06:24.470
right here where we are.

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:29.070
So, the book "Extreme Weather" talks a lot
about those scenarios, including tornadoes.

